This paper deals with formal methods for security and anonymity, which are typically studied in the computer science sub-category of cryptography (cs.CR). The paper specifically focuses on the quantitative analysis of information leakage, which involves mathematical techniques and algorithms, suggesting that it could also fit into the sub-categories of logic in computer science (cs.LO) and information theory (cs.IT). The paper also mentions the use of model-checking, which is a technique commonly used in the sub-category of distributed systems (cs.DS). Finally, the paper proposes algorithms for computing leakage in probabilistic systems, which could also place it in the sub-category of programming languages (cs.PL), as probabilistic programming is an active area of research in that field.
